TY  - JOUR
T1  - Trade with Nominal Rigidities: Understanding the Unemployment and                         Welfare Effects of the China Shock
AU  - Rodríguez-Clare, Andrés
AU  - Ulate, Mauricio
AU  - Vásquez, José P.
Y1  - 2025/08/25
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2026/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/738344
DO  - 10.1086/738344
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 626
EP  - 664
VL  - 134
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We present a dynamic quantitative trade and migration model that incorporates downward nominal wage rigidities and show how this framework can generate changes in unemployment and labor participation that match those uncovered by the empirical literature studying the China shock. We find that the China shock leads to average welfare increases in most US states, including many that experience unemployment during the transition. However, nominal rigidities reduce the overall US gains by around two-thirds. In addition, there are 18 states that experience welfare losses in the presence of downward nominal wage rigidity that would have experienced gains without it.
AB  - We present a dynamic quantitative trade and migration model that incorporates downward nominal wage rigidities and show how this framework can generate changes in unemployment and labor participation that match those uncovered by the empirical literature studying the China shock. We find that the China shock leads to average welfare increases in most US states, including many that experience unemployment during the transition. However, nominal rigidities reduce the overall US gains by around two-thirds. In addition, there are 18 states that experience welfare losses in the presence of downward nominal wage rigidity that would have experienced gains without it.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/738344
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/738344
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Screening with Persuasion
AU  - Bergemann, Dirk
AU  - Heumann, Tibor
AU  - Morris, Stephen
Y1  - 2025/08/25
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2026/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/738342
DO  - 10.1086/738342
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 570
EP  - 625
VL  - 134
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We analyze a nonlinear pricing model where the seller controls both product pricing (screening) and buyer information about their own values (persuasion). We prove that the optimal mechanism always consists of finitely many signals and items, even with a continuum of buyer values. The seller optimally pools buyer values and reduces product variety to minimize informational rents. We show that value pooling is optimal even for finite value distributions if their entropy exceeds a critical threshold. We also provide sufficient conditions under which the optimal menu restricts offering to a single item.
AB  - We analyze a nonlinear pricing model where the seller controls both product pricing (screening) and buyer information about their own values (persuasion). We prove that the optimal mechanism always consists of finitely many signals and items, even with a continuum of buyer values. The seller optimally pools buyer values and reduces product variety to minimize informational rents. We show that value pooling is optimal even for finite value distributions if their entropy exceeds a critical threshold. We also provide sufficient conditions under which the optimal menu restricts offering to a single item.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/738342
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/738342
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Minimum Wage and Individual Worker Productivity: Evidence from a Large US Retailer
AU  - Coviello, Decio
AU  - Deserranno, Erika
AU  - Persico, Nicola
Y1  - 2022/04/12
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/720397
DO  - 10.1086/720397
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2315
EP  - 2360
VL  - 130
IS  - 9
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We study workers who are employed by a large US retailer, work in many store locations, and are paid based on performance. By means of a border-discontinuity analysis, we document that workers become more productive and are terminated less often after a minimum wage increase. These effects are stronger among workers whose pay is more often supported by the minimum wage. However, when workers are monitored less intensely, the minimum wage depresses productivity. We interpret these findings through an efficiency wage model. After a minimum wage increase, profits decrease, and a calibration exercise suggests that worker welfare increases.
AB  - We study workers who are employed by a large US retailer, work in many store locations, and are paid based on performance. By means of a border-discontinuity analysis, we document that workers become more productive and are terminated less often after a minimum wage increase. These effects are stronger among workers whose pay is more often supported by the minimum wage. However, when workers are monitored less intensely, the minimum wage depresses productivity. We interpret these findings through an efficiency wage model. After a minimum wage increase, profits decrease, and a calibration exercise suggests that worker welfare increases.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/720397
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/720397
Y2  - 2026/04/24
